  <h2>Alluvium: Data Availability & Batching</h2>
  <p>
    Silica separates <strong>data dissemination</strong> from <strong>ordering</strong>. Alluvium provides data availability without imposing a global order:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>High-throughput batching:</strong> Nodes create micro-batches of transactions (50-200 per second) and broadcast them as DAG vertices.</li>
    <li><strong>Data availability:</strong> Each batch is erasure-coded (Reed-Solomon) so any 2/3 of nodes can reconstruct the full data, even if some nodes are slow or offline.</li>
    <li><strong>Parallel processing:</strong> Batches propagate concurrently across all validators, not sequentially.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Result: the network is always accumulating transactions, not waiting for one block to finish before the next begins.</p>

  <h2>Crystallite: Ordering &amp; Consensus</h2>
  <p>
    Once batches are widely available, Crystallite applies deterministic commit rules to produce a <strong>canonical global ordering</strong>.
    This is the network's ordering source of truth.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Leaderless ordering:</strong> No single proposer dictates order; commit rules select an unambiguous sequence.</li>
    <li><strong>Deterministic output:</strong> The committed sequence is the only ordering truth (no re-ordering later).</li>
    <li><strong>Byzantine-resilient:</strong> Safety holds under adversarial behavior; liveness resumes once the network can make progress.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="info-box">
    <h3>Timeline of a Transaction</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>T+0ms:</strong> Tx hits a Gateway node</li>
      <li><strong>T+50ms:</strong> Included in a micro-batch</li>
      <li><strong>T+150ms:</strong> Batch propagated, erasure-coded</li>
      <li><strong>T+400ms:</strong> Crystallite produces a committed ordering</li>
      <li><strong>T+500ms:</strong> The Striation executes in parallel lanes (Striae)</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Total:</strong> &lt;500ms from send to lithified finality. No confirmations to babysit.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Lithification: Finality</h2>
  <p>
    Finality is the irreversible commitment of state once the committed ordering is applied.
    Lithification is the point of no return.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Irreversible commitment:</strong> Once lithified, transactions do not roll back or reorg.</li>
    <li><strong>Timing-independent safety:</strong> Safety does not depend on synchronized clocks or fixed timeout schedules.</li>
    <li><strong>Recovery-friendly:</strong> Finality certificates and anchors make recovery and monitoring straightforward.</li>
  </ul>


